</li>
</ul>

</div>

<h2 class="sectionedit9" id="manufacturing">Manufacturing</h2>
<div class="level2">

</div>

<h3 class="sectionedit10" id="industrialization_and_fabrication">Industrialization and fabrication</h3>
<div class="level3">
<ul>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?feature=player_detailpage&amp;v=35jWSQXku74#t=123s" class="urlextern" title="http://www.youtube.com/watch?feature=player_detailpage&amp;v=35jWSQXku74#t=123s"  rel="nofollow">The Fabrication of Integrated Circuits </a>  </div>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z47Gv2cdFtA&amp;feature=related" class="urlextern" title="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z47Gv2cdFtA&amp;feature=related"  rel="nofollow">Fairchild Briefing on Integrated Circuits </a>← old, but very good explained</div>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TXvhyvwttRE&amp;feature=fvwrel" class="urlextern" title="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TXvhyvwttRE&amp;feature=fvwrel"  rel="nofollow">Fabrication Process for CMOS Device</a> even more detail about the einzelne processes.</div>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=26fkuAY8jKs&amp;feature=related" class="urlextern" title="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=26fkuAY8jKs&amp;feature=related"  rel="nofollow">Microchip production part 2</a> even more insight!</div>
</li>
</ul>

<p>
Some catchwords from the videos:
</p>
<ol>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> 400 process steps are required along with 15-20 different photographic negative masks</div>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> production of a wafer takes about 3 Weeks</div>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> bla bla</div>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> Last step involves making the connection between the various elements of the IC. Minuscule vacuum deposited layer of Al</div>
</li>
</ol>

</div>

<h3 class="sectionedit11" id="package_or_chip_carrier">Package or Chip carrier</h3>
<div class="level3">

<p>
First the slicing, then the 400 processes and then the dicing. Now we put each die into a package carrier:
</p>
<ul>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VwOEQodkBrY&amp;feature=related" class="urlextern" title="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VwOEQodkBrY&amp;feature=related"  rel="nofollow">Wedge Bonding Process</a></div>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pajE4Bi6Xts&amp;feature=related" class="urlextern" title="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pajE4Bi6Xts&amp;feature=related"  rel="nofollow">Gold Ball Bonding</a></div>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_qKThIzDaP0&amp;feature=related" class="urlextern" title="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_qKThIzDaP0&amp;feature=related"  rel="nofollow">Bonder</a></div>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Package on package" class="interwiki iw_wp" title="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Package on package">PoP</a> is implemented e.g. by the <a href="http://www.omappedia.com/images/5/54/PandaBoard_Setup.png" class="urlextern" title="http://www.omappedia.com/images/5/54/PandaBoard_Setup.png"  rel="nofollow">Pandaboard</a></div>
</li>
</ul>

<p>
As the the Pentium Pro included CPU and L2-Cache on one <em>&quot;package&quot; or &quot;chip&quot;</em> but still on two distinct <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Die (integrated circuit)" class="interwiki iw_wp" title="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Die (integrated circuit)">dies</a>, and the first intel QuadCores, were actually 2 distinct dies, with two CPU-Cores on each packaged on one Chip, so can a SoC consists of more then one single die.
</p>

</div>

<h3 class="sectionedit12" id="the_pcb">The PCB</h3>
<div class="level3">

<p>
The <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Printed circuit board" class="interwiki iw_wp" title="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Printed circuit board">Printed circuit board</a> is for combining more ICs (Chips), like a CPU-Chip, Memory-Chip, Resistors and connectors for Ethernet [RJ-45], Current, etc.
</p>

<p>
A PCB can have more layers! More layers become necessary the crossing of pathways cannot be avoided. PC graphic boards have 6 to 8 layers, motherboards <img src="../../lib/images/smileys/fixme.gif" class="icon" alt="FIXME" /> layers. PCBs for a simple router can have <img src="../../lib/images/smileys/fixme.gif" class="icon" alt="FIXME" /> layers.
</p>

</div>

